AI Guard rule taxonomy — pipelock (Apache License 2.0)
------------------------------------------------------------------------
The prompt-injection and secret/exfil (DLP) rule TAXONOMY used by the AI
guard under `src/app-layer/ai/guard/` — the rule categories
(ignore-previous / system-role-injection / instruction-override /
tool-poisoning / exfil-directive; API key / bearer-or-JWT / private-key /
seed-phrase / high-entropy-secret) and several of the pattern shapes in
`src/app-layer/ai/guard/patterns.ts` — are ADAPTED from the pipelock
project, used here under the terms of the Apache License, Version 2.0.

pipelock is used as a taxonomy blueprint only. It is NOT a dependency of
this project: no pipelock code is imported, linked, or redistributed; the
guard is an independent TypeScript-native reimplementation.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Agent-action receipts — pipelock (Apache License 2.0 CORE)
------------------------------------------------------------------------
inflect-compliance ingests and verifies mediator-signed AI-agent "action
receipts" produced by pipelock (https://github.com/luckyPipewrench/pipelock),
an "AI agent firewall for MCP security".

We use ONLY the pipelock Apache-2.0-licensed CORE receipt format (the
`action_record` container with a top-level Ed25519 `signature` / `signer_key`
and hash-chain fields). We do NOT use, link, bundle, or depend on any pipelock
feature governed by the Elastic License 2.0 (the "fleet" features, including the
`fleet-receipt` DSSE envelope format).

No pipelock source code is vendored or redistributed here. We do not depend on
any pipelock npm package (there is no TypeScript verifier SDK); the Ed25519
signature is verified natively using Node's built-in `crypto` module against the
CORE receipt canonicalization. Portions of pipelock governed by the Elastic
License 2.0 are NOT used by this product.

